1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
 4 pounds. Paid in blankets, clothing and hardware, roughly 11 cents an acre.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:09,000
 As settlements grew along the shore, so did the shipwrecks.

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:16,000
 Between 1846 and 1848 alone, more than 120 vessels wrecked along the New Jersey coast.

4
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:22,000
 And with each disaster came a damning rumor that the locals were not just salvaging the wreckage.

5
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:24,000
 They were causing it.

6
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:29,000
 The people of Monmouth County were branded bandits and land pirates.

7
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:34,000
 Newspapers accused them of hanging false lights to confuse ships captains,

8
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:38,000
 driving vessels onto sand bars so they could plunder the cargo.

9
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:45,000
 In 1799, the New Jersey legislature made it a crime to display false lights to induce a shipwreck.

